  an <code>-enterprise</code> suffix after the version number, for example: <code>neo4j:2026.05.0-enterprise</code>.
  Community Edition tags have no suffix, for example <code>neo4j:2026.05.0</code>.
  The latest Neo4j Enterprise Edition release is available as <code>neo4j:enterprise</code>.</p>
  re which base image to use or have no preference, just use the default of <code>neo4j:2026.05.0</code>.</p>
  <pre class="highlightjs highlight"><code class="language-none hljs">neo4j:2026.05.0-trixie              # debian 13 community
  neo4j:2026.05.0-enterprise-ubi10   # redhat UBI10 enterprise
  neo4j:2026.05.0                    # debian 13 community
  neo4j:2026.05.0-enterprise         # debian 13 enterprise</code></pre>
  ass="highlightjs highlight"><code class="language-shell hljs" data-lang="shell">docker run \
      --publish=7474:7474 --publish=7687:7687 \
      neo4j:2026.05.0</code></pre>
  <p>You can try out your Neo4j container by opening <em>http://localhost:7474/</em> (the Neo4j&#8217;s Browser interface) in a web browser.
  ass="highlightjs highlight"><code class="language-shell hljs" data-lang="shell">docker run \
      --publish=7474:7474 --publish=7687:7687 \
      --env NEO4J_AUTH=neo4j/your_password \
      neo4j:2026.05.0</code></pre>
  <h2 id="docker-auth"><a class="anchor" href="#docker-auth"></a>Using <code>NEO4J_AUTH</code> to set an initial password</h2>
   can set the initial password for the database directly by specifying the <code>NEO4J_AUTH</code> in your run directive:</p>
  ass="highlightjs highlight"><code class="language-shell hljs" data-lang="shell">docker run \
      --publish=7474:7474 --publish=7687:7687 \
      --env NEO4J_AUTH=neo4j/your_password \
      neo4j:2026.05.0</code></pre>
  <p>Alternatively, you can disable authentication by specifying <code>NEO4J_AUTH</code> to <code>none</code>:</p>
  ighlightjs highlight"><code class="language-shell hljs" data-lang="shell">--env NEO4J_AUTH=none</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Setting <code>NEO4J_AUTH</code> does not override the existing authentication.</strong></p>
   mounted a <em>/data</em> volume containing an existing database, setting <code>NEO4J_AUTH</code> will have no effect because that database already has authentication configured.
  _options"><a class="anchor" href="#_useful_docker_run_options"></a>Useful <code>docker run</code> options</h2>
  <caption class="title">Table 2. Options for <code>docker run</code></caption>
  <td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><code>docker run --name myneo4j neo4j</code></p></td>
  <td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><code>docker run -p7687:7687 neo4j</code></p></td>
  <td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><code>docker run -d neo4j</code></p></td>
  <td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><code>docker run -v $HOME/neo4j/data:/data neo4j</code></p></td>
  <td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><code>docker run --env NEO4J_AUTH=neo4j/your_password neo4j</code></p></td>
  <td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><code>docker run --user="$(id -u):$(id -g)" neo4j</code></p></td>
  <td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><code>docker run --restart always</code></p></td>
  <p>Output full list of <code>docker run</code> options</p>
  <td class="tableblock halign-left valign-top"><p class="tableblock"><code>docker run --help</code></p></td>
  <p>This is an example command to save the <code>neo4j:2026.05.0</code> image to a <code>.tar</code> file:</p>
  lass="language-shell hljs" data-lang="shell">docker save -o neo4j-2026.05.0.tar neo4j:2026.05.0</code></pre>
